<Content>Very Convenient But Not Up To Hilton Standards After a long flight, never having been to Mexico City before, and only speaking a smattering of Spanish, it was very convenient for me to simply get through immigration and customs, walk down the terminal corridor, and go up a couple of escalators and an elevator to arrive at my hotel.Unfortunately, after I'd been in my room and unpacked, I discovered that the lights in the bathroom did not work. I was too tired and it was too late to try and switch rooms so I managed by the hall light, but it was definitely a bother.I only stayed one night, and overall, my room was fine. The A/C worked really well, which for me was a very good thing. With the entire airport concourse below, you had a lot of options as far as food. They called me a taxi the next day for my meeting and I later discovered on my trip back that their taxi charged me about double what another service charged me to drive me back (350 pesos versus 180). Not a huge difference dollar-wise, but still something to beware of.They had WiFi access in the room, but to connect, you had to call the front desk to get a passcode. Again, not a big deal but given other existing technologies, an unnecessary complication.All in all, considering that this was a Hilton-brand property and not one of their budget brands, I was underwhelmed. 
